#  Blackjack Pershing: The Man Who Got America's Enemy #1

In the early days of World War I, General John J. Pershing was charged with defeating the Central Powers, made up of Germany and its allies. He did so by leading the American Expeditionary Force (AEF) in Europe and routing the enemy in a number of historic battles. But his biggest achievement may have been capturing or killing the elusive "Beast of Berlin," General Erich von Ludendorff.

Ludendorff was one of the most prized targets of the AEF. He was seen as a mastermind behind Germany's war effort and was ultimately responsible for many of its military setbacks. After years of pursuit by Pershing and his men, Ludendorff was finally cornered and captured in November 1918—just two weeks before the end of the war.

Pershing's success against Ludendorff led to him being called "Blackjack" by his troops. The nickname stuck throughout his career, and he eventually became known as one of America's most distinguished military leaders.

#  How Blackjack Pershing Became Known As Black Jack

