After graduating from West Point in 1886, Second Lieutenant Pershing was assigned to the Fourth Cavalry Regiment at Fort Huachuca in Arizona. In 1890 he was made a captain and transferred to the Philippines, where he fought in the Spanish-American War (1898). After the war he remained in the Philippines as military advisor to the Philippine government.

In 1902 Captain Pershing returned to the United States and took command of a cavalry regiment at Fort Bliss, Texas. In 1906 he was promoted to brigadier general and made commander of the Eighth Cavalry Brigade at Camp Beauregard, Louisiana.

In 1916 General Pershing was named commander of American forces in Europe during World War I (1914-1918). He quickly built up an impressive record, leading his troops from one victory to another. His most famous victory came at the Battle of Saint-Mihiel, in which American and French forces crushed a large German army.

After the war General Pershing led the American occupation of Germany. He retired from active duty in 1924 but remained involved with military affairs as head of the Army Board of Generals and chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. He died on July 15, 1948, and was buried with full military honors at Arlington National Cemetery.

